d receptors and can have either excitatory or inhibitory effects","Both D1-like and D2-like receptors are ligand-gated channels and have an excitatory effect","Both are G-protein coupled receptors; D1-like receptors are excitatory and D2-like receptors are inhibitory","Neither receptor family, all G-protein coupled receptors, has consistent excitatory or inhibitory effects"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth are G-protein coupled receptors; D1-like receptors are excitatory and D2-like receptors are inhibitory\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the classification. D1-like receptors (D1 and D5) produce excitatory effects. D2-like receptors (D2, D3, and D4) produce inhibitory effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ED1-like receptors are G-protein coupled receptors and are inhibitory\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as D1-like receptors are excitatory\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth D1-like and D2-like receptors are G-protein coupled receptors and can have either excitatory or inhibitory effects\u003C/strong\u003E - Each receptor family has consistent effects based on their G-protein coupling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth D1-like and D2-like receptors are ligand-gated channels and have an excitatory effect\u003C/strong\u003E - These are G-protein coupled receptors, not ligand-gated channels, and D2-like receptors are inhibitory\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeither receptor family, all G-protein coupled receptors, has consistent excitatory or inhibitory effects\u003C/strong\u003E - Each family has consistent effects based on their G-protein coupling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis classification system helps explain why different dopamine receptor subtypes have distinct therapeutic applications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["D1-like receptors (D1, D5) are coupled to Gs proteins and produce excitatory effects.","D2-like receptors (D2, D3, D4) are coupled to Gi proteins and produce inhibitory effects.","Understanding dopaminergic receptor classification helps predict therapeutic effects of dopaminergic drugs."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62020"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16796"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62020"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T16:46:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T16:46:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9487"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76523"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"ht